<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-11-20T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-11-20T23:00:00-05:00" n="256" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d256">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77 Chinese Eastern/454:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-11-21T12:00:00+08:00">November 21,
                                1929—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received November 21—6
                            a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>1020. Following from American Consul in charge at Mukden: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“November 20, 5 a.m. According to confidential information
                                    received from official source, Chinese lost 2,000 men killed up
                                    to yesterday on the western front. Twenty-seven Soviet aircraft
                                    are reported <pb facs="0489" n="345" xml:id="pg_345"/> to have
                                    dropped more than 300 bombs which did much damage; fighting
                                    still continues, with Chinese forces reported to be generally
                                    holding their positions.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>